 =20
   =20
      Succession
   =20
 =20

If you are a top executive, but not the chief executive officer, at a big i=
nvestment bank, and you are not particularly near retirement, probably the =
job that you want more than any other job is to be CEO of your bank. And th=
en your second choice would probably be to be CEO of a different bank. Or  =
 Carlyle Group. Lots of CEO jobs out there, and if you=E2=80=99ve been doin=
g it this long you probably want one of them. Retiring as a top-executive-b=
ut-not-CEO of your bank is going to feel just a tiny bit like failure.=C2=
=A0
From the bank=E2=80=99s perspective, this is bad: The bank wants all of its=
 top executives to be energetic brilliant people who=C2=A0could=C2=A0run th=
e bank, who would make great CEOs elsewhere, but who nonetheless choose to =
stay at the bank without a shot at the CEO job. There are various ways to c=
reate that sort of loyalty:
=09Money. If being the No. 7 person at your firm pays more than being the C=
EO elsewhere then hey that=E2=80=99s great. There are businesses where this=
 works, though it is hard to pull off in investment banking.=09Culture. If =
all of your top executives have worked all their lives at your firm, if all=
 their friends are there, if they look down on every other firm and find th=
e idea of working elsewhere unimaginable, then they will stay.=09Partnershi=
p. This is related, but slightly different. I used to work at Goldman Sachs=
 Group Inc., which more than most of the big public investment banks tried =
to retain   some of its old partnership culture, though there are a lot of =
reports that it is fraying under its current CEO, David Solomon.=C2=A0One a=
dvantage of that culture is that, in a partnership, everyone gets to feel a=
 bit like a CEO. =E2=80=9CSince the late 1800s, Goldman partners have weigh=
ed in on the firm=E2=80=99s direction,=E2=80=9D the Wall Street Journal   w=
rote in June. =E2=80=9CPartners sometimes overruled the CEO or persuaded hi=
m to go along with their plans. For a long time, the CEO was viewed as one =
of many, less a benign dictator and more the bank=E2=80=99s public face and=
 standard-bearer.=E2=80=9D If you can make =E2=80=9Cpartner=E2=80=9D=C2=A0f=
eel=C2=A0like the top job, rather than =E2=80=9CCEO,=E2=80=9D you can keep =
a lot of good people around feeling satisfied that they=E2=80=99ve made it =
to the top.=09Constant coups? If every top executive=C2=A0could=C2=A0become=
 CEO by bumping off the current CEO, they might stay motivated. This has pr=
oblems.=09I don=E2=80=99t know, you couldmake all the top people sign 10-ye=
ar employment contracts 15 minutes before you announce the new CEO.

Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Sridhar Natarajan reports on the apparently amicable ra=
ce at Morgan Stanley=C2=A0to succeed CEO James Gorman:

Gorman, 65, is running Wall Street=E2=80=99s most closely watched horse rac=
e, vowing to have his successor in place in less than a year.
But what=E2=80=99s especially striking is Gorman=E2=80=99s other declaratio=
n: He wants to defy deeply entrenched norms with a bloodless handoff =E2=80=
=94 in which the rejected finalists stay, avoiding the usual cascade of sha=
keups and senior departures. =E2=80=A6
=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s a daring bet in an industry where fragile egos and raw a=
mbition make for messy handovers, sometimes derailing even the best-perform=
ing firms.
Mike Mayo, the skeptic-in-chief among bank analysts, remains unconvinced.
=E2=80=9CThe road is littered with CEO succession that results in upheaval =
of those in the upper ranks,=E2=80=9D Mayo said. =E2=80=9CI just think it=
=E2=80=99s going to be a challenge to keep the team as cohesive as they cur=
rently are.=E2=80=9D

The three leading candidates =E2=80=94=C2=A0Ted Pick,=C2=A0Andy Saperstein=
=C2=A0and Dan Simkowitz =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Care known to dine together =
frequently and even appear to enjoy each others=E2=80=99 company,=E2=80=9D =
but of course that=E2=80=99s how they feel=C2=A0now. Now they are trying to=
 win a competition in which they are, apparently, judged on how nicely they=
 work with each other. Once two of them lose that competition they might fe=
el different.
Also this is good:
In one sign of the uncertainty, two senior colleagues privately bemoaned th=
at they might not be close enough to whomever wins. They wouldn=E2=80=99t w=
ant to be hitched to the wrong candidate and lose clout.
I thought they were all best friends!

 =20
   =20
      Platforms
   =20
 =20

Here are three broad theories of venture investing:
=09The job of a venture capitalist is to evaluate a lot of potential invest=
ments, choose the best ones, and make those.=09The job of a venture capital=
ist is to get access to=C2=A0the best investments, and then make them.=09Th=
e job of a venture capitalist is to invest in companies and then=C2=A0make=
=C2=A0those companies better, by serving on boards and imparting wisdom and=
 making introductions and helping the companies hire employees and get cust=
omers.

The job is deal selection, or deal flow, or operational improvements. Obvio=
usly all three theories have some truth to them, and you can try to do all =
three things, but to some extent you are going to have to make choices abou=
t what to prioritize. We   talked a  lot, in the   recent   boom, about Tig=
er Global, a hedge fund that got into late-stage private tech investing wit=
h a very differentiated thesis. The thesis was roughly =E2=80=9Cwe will thr=
ow money at every deal that comes in the door, at high valuations, without =
much due diligence and certainly without pestering the company to put us on=
 the board and listen to our wisdom. When founders hear about our approach,=
 they will think =E2=80=98oh man that sounds good,=E2=80=99 and they will c=
ome to us first, and we will get much better deal flow than everyone else, =
and the job is deal flow.=E2=80=9D This honestly does not seem to have work=
ed out=C2=A0great=C2=A0for Tiger Global, but I do admire their willingness =
to make a bold contrarian bet.=C2=A0
Obviously lots of other VCs are out there like =E2=80=9Cwe choose all three=
: We provide lots of wisdom and help to our portfolio companies, which make=
s lots of founders come to us first, so we get a lot of deal flow, and then=
 with our wisdom we choose only the best deals and pass on the rest.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0
Anyway here (via Byrne Hobart) is  a Crunchbase study=C2=A0examining ventur=
e capital firms with =E2=80=9Cplatform=E2=80=9D teams, =E2=80=9Cdefined as =
the collection of roles focused on specific non-investment functions, like =
community building, fund operations, marketing and business development,=E2=
=80=9D roughly a proxy for the operational-improvements part of the VC job
  [2]
:

Results of the study indicate a strong correlation between increased invest=
ment in platform teams and superior fund returns.
The correlation neither suggests that the relationship is causal nor does i=
t imply that a fund must have a platform function to generate successful re=
turns. But, it is interesting to note that funds that had significant platf=
orm teams outperformed those funds without platform teams by 1,100 basis po=
ints in Net IRR and 0.5x in TVPI over the most recent decade.

You could imagine causal explanations of the form =E2=80=9Cdoing stuff to h=
elp your portfolio companies actually makes them perform better,=E2=80=9D o=
r of the form =E2=80=9Coffering stuff to help your portfolio companies make=
s founders more likely to bring you good deals,=E2=80=9D or both I suppose.=
 Or not-quite-causal explanations like =E2=80=9CVC firms with platform team=
s are also the ones with a culture of spending some time thinking about the=
 companies that they invest in and how they work, and the other approach of=
 throwing money at everything that comes in the door turns out to underperf=
orm.=E2=80=9D

 =20
   =20
      Activism
   =20
 =20

Here are two broad theories of activist investing:
=09Some companies have good opportunities but bad management, and an activi=
st investor can buy some stock, harangue the board and management to make c=
hanges, and improve the company=E2=80=99s business.=09Some companies could =
be bought at a premium by other companies, and an activist investor can buy=
 some stock, agitate for a sale, make the sale happen and collect the premi=
um.
  [3]



That is, the job can be operational improvements, or it can be sort of M&A =
matchmaking. Intuitively =E2=80=9CM&A matchmaking=E2=80=9D makes more sense=
: What are the odds that an activist hedge fund manager has better ideas fo=
r how to run a widget factory than the widget company chief executive offic=
er? The widget CEO specializes in widgets, but the activist manager can spe=
cialize in making deals happen.
The operational-improvements model could, I suppose, work through the cycle=
; there=E2=80=99s always some company somewhere that can be improved. The M=
&A-matchmaker model does kind of depend on the merger market though. Here=
=E2=80=99s  a Wall Street Journal story about how activists are having a to=
ugh time in a tough merger market:

Activists generally seek out big returns by accumulating stakes in companie=
s and then drumming up lots of noise in hopes of forcing boards to make cha=
nges or outright pushing businesses to sell. In fact, they tend to favor th=
e latter as it=E2=80=99s an almost surefire way to make a buck. But with fe=
wer deals in the market, these firms have had one less arrow in their quive=
rs.
Predicting the stock market in 2023 has been tough for many investors, said=
 Bill Anderson, a senior managing director at Evercore and head of the firm=
=E2=80=99s global activism-defense business.
=E2=80=9CBut this year=E2=80=99s downdraft in leveraged buyout activity has=
 been really tough for activists,=E2=80=9D Anderson said. =E2=80=9CThe deal=
s they thought they would have to help their returns haven=E2=80=99t been o=
ut there.=E2=80=9D

Also, in a market where the biggest companies keep getting bigger, activism=
 is harder because, what, you=E2=80=99re gonna do activism at Apple?
  [4]

Plus, as Anderson pointed out, the handful of tech companies that have play=
ed an outsize role in driving the stock market higher this year=E2=80=93lik=
e Apple, Alphabet, Meta Platforms, Microsoft, Nvidia, Amazon.com and Tesla=
=E2=80=93are =E2=80=9Cnot really activist targets.=E2=80=9D
The activist model is about taking smallish bad companies and making them b=
etter, but the action these days is in huge good companies getting better o=
n their own.

 =20
   =20
      Yellow
   =20
 =20

An investment firm called=C2=A0MFN Partners bought like half the stock of t=
rucking company Yellow Corp. the week before it went bankrupt, which was re=
ally a surprising choice, and if they make money on the trade I=E2=80=99m g=
oing to be so impressed. We have   talked about   this a few times, and=C2=
=A0 here=E2=80=99s the latest:

Bankrupt trucking giant Yellow said it has enough real estate and equipment=
 it can sell to cover $1.2 billion it borrowed from the U.S. government and=
 private lenders led by Apollo Global Management.
An appraisal last year of Yellow=E2=80=99s trucks, equipment and other prop=
erty came out to $2.1 billion, Yellow=E2=80=99s lawyer Patrick Nash said at=
 the company=E2=80=99s first appearance in bankruptcy court since filing fo=
r chapter 11 on Sunday. =E2=80=A6
The company entered bankruptcy with a $142 million loan from Apollo lined u=
p to fund the liquidation process. Yellow didn=E2=80=99t seek court approva=
l for that financing on Wednesday because it received competing proposals t=
o finance the bankruptcy case from trucking rival Estes Express Lines and f=
rom investment firm MFN Partners, Nash said at the hearing.
Boston-based MFN recently accumulated more than 42% of Yellow=E2=80=99s sha=
res, which staged an improbable rally as the company approached bankruptcy.=
=C2=A0
For the company=E2=80=99s stock to have any value in bankruptcy, it would h=
ave to pay off not only its secured obligations but all unsecured claims in=
 full. Yellow on Wednesday listed total current liabilities of $1.92 billio=
n, up from $717 million at the end of 2022. Its cash holdings on its balanc=
e sheet contracted to $112.8 million at the end of the quarter from $235.1 =
million at the end of 2022.

It=E2=80=99s pretty close! Like $2.1 billion appraised value plus $113 mill=
ion of cash minus $1.92 billion of liabilities minus the cost of bankruptcy=
 minus the risk of getting that appraised value in bankruptcy.=C2=A0It does=
 seem like the equity value is=C2=A0roughly=C2=A0zero, but there is some ma=
rgin for error; MFN paid something like $22.9 million for its stock, which =
on a $2 billion enterprise value is roughly zero. What a fun trade.=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      Pepperoni
   =20
 =20

The stereotypical way that a management consulting interview works is that =
you get asked questions like =E2=80=9Chow much pepperoni=C2=A0 is sold in t=
he US every year,=E2=80=9D and then you reason your way to some estimate of=
 the answer. This stuff is a classic of management consulting interviewing =
not because you are expected to know the answer, or because management cons=
ultants spend their days guessing how much pepperoni is sold in the US each=
 year, but because the process of answering the question demonstrates your =
ability to reason through a problem, think on the fly=C2=A0and act confiden=
t in meetings, and also it=C2=A0gives some sense of your practical understa=
nding of the world. Or something. I don=E2=80=99t know. I have not been in =
a management consulting interview since college, and I wasn=E2=80=99t great=
 at them then. That=E2=80=99s not the point. The point is that management c=
onsultants do not actually spend their days guessing how much pepperoni is =
sold in the US each year.   Or do they?

A few weeks into his college summer internship at a consulting firm in 2015=
, a guy (let=E2=80=99s call him Calvin) got his big chance to make a good i=
mpression. He was assigned to help a private equity firm assess an acquisit=
ion target=E2=80=94in this case, a company that manufactured pepperoni. =E2=
=80=9CI was 21 years old, researching questions I don=E2=80=99t know if any=
one knows the answer to, like the market size for pepperoni in the US,=E2=
=80=9D says Calvin, who asked that his name not be used to preserve his cur=
rent professional reputation.
After two 80-hour weeks of research, Calvin=E2=80=99s peers in the sweaty i=
ntern bullpen in an office off New York=E2=80=99s Times Square were ready t=
o present their findings. But he still lacked the crucial number. =E2=80=9C=
I was the bottleneck, and I wasn=E2=80=99t doing a great job communicating =
to my boss,=E2=80=9D he says. His solution? =E2=80=9CI found a claim from s=
ome executive online that the market size for pepperoni is enough that you =
could blanket the entire USA with a thin layer,=E2=80=9D says Calvin. He sp=
ent hours putting together and executing a plan. He calculated the area of =
the entire continental US (3,120,426 square miles). Then he came up with th=
e area of a single pepperoni slice: If the diameter of a circular slice of =
pepperoni is half an inch, each pepperoni is 0.196 square inches. The area =
of the continental US, divided by the area of a single pepperoni slice, equ=
als 15,920,541 slices, which he labeled the national pepperoni volume. Fina=
lly, he multiplied that volume by price (10=C2=A2 per slice, based on his m=
arket research) to come up with the country=E2=80=99s pepperoni market size=
 at $1,592,054 per year.
When Calvin tracked down his bosses to deliver this key figure, they weren=
=E2=80=99t interested. They considered his approach ridiculous.

What? What? They worked at a management consulting firm! They hired people =
specifically for their propensity, when confronted with a question like =E2=
=80=9Chow much pepperoni is sold in the US each year,=E2=80=9D to use input=
s like =E2=80=9Cthe area of the continental US.=E2=80=9D They should have p=
romoted him. What an amazing story. This is like if a utility company came =
to McKinsey & Co. and said =E2=80=9Cwe need to design some manhole covers, =
what shape should we make them,=E2=80=9D and the first-day McKinsey intern =
was like =E2=80=9Cwait wait  I will handle this.=E2=80=9D
I guess my only quibble is that=C2=A0the math in this anecdote is wildly wr=
ong: The calculation divides 3 million square miles by 0.196 pepperonis per=
 square inch to get a far-too-low 16 million pepperonis per year, or just $=
1.6 million at 10 cents per pepperoni. If you do the math correctly, then=
=C2=A03.1 million square miles is=C2=A0roughly  12.5 quadrillion square inc=
hes, or roughly 64 quadrillion pepperonis, or roughly $6.4 quadrillion of p=
epperoni sales per year at 10 cents a piece, or roughly 60=C2=A0times the g=
ross domestic product of  the world. Bullish for this pepperoni acquisition=
.
(Since I wrote that paragraph, Businessweek corrected the math to get $6.4 =
quadrillion. Or, =E2=80=9Ccorrected.=E2=80=9D)
Anyway that anecdote is from Charley Locke=E2=80=99s   Bloomberg Businesswe=
ek story about interns, which is full of weird intern anecdotes, including =
this guy who needed a fraud intern:
When Hoi Wong landed an internship at a marketing firm in France through an=
 undergraduate job portal at his college, he assumed he was all set for his=
 Emily in Paris summer. When he got there, he realized the =E2=80=9Cmarketi=
ng firm=E2=80=9D was located in a man=E2=80=99s apartment and that his job =
would mostly consist of making slides to promote work the company falsely c=
laimed to have done. =E2=80=9CIt was a sketchy internship, but it was fine =
until one morning when he woke up late and came out of his room in his unde=
rwear,=E2=80=9D says Wong, now an MBA candidate at the University of Califo=
rnia at Berkeley=E2=80=99s Haas School of Business. =E2=80=9CIn retrospect,=
 I should have done some due diligence about him and the company.=E2=80=9D

 =20
   =20
      =E2=80=9CI want my bribes back=E2=80=9D
   =20
 =20

Ahahaha   great stuff:

Private equity investor John B. Wilson has already gotten his fraud convict=
ion overturned in the sprawling =E2=80=9CVarsity Blues=E2=80=9D college adm=
issions scandal. Now he wants the $1 million he paid to the scheme=E2=80=99=
s mastermind back.
Wilson, founder of Hyannis Port Capital, was among dozens of parents charge=
d with taking part in the scam to cheat their kids=E2=80=99 way into elite =
institutions.
He argues that since he was cleared by an appeals court of paying bribes to=
 get his twin daughters into Harvard and Stanford, the government should re=
turn the $500,000 in fees for each child he paid to a corrupt admissions st=
rategist, William =E2=80=9CRick=E2=80=9D Singer, in a ruse concocted by the=
 FBI.

But they got into Harvard and Stanford! He absolutely got what he paid for;=
 the admissions consulting worked. The fact is that Singer funneled the mon=
ey illegally to college coaches, rather than following=C2=A0  the correct (=
and more expensive) procedure for college-admissions bribery (paying the co=
llege to name buildings), but the victims of that crime are the colleges, n=
ot Wilson. He got a bargain.

