19a23cB36b3cb51" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">  Carlyle Group</a>. Lots of CEO jobs out there, a=
nd if you=E2=80=99ve been doing it this long you probably want one of them.=
 Retiring as a top-executive-but-not-CEO of your bank is going to feel just=
 a tiny bit like failure.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From the bank=E2=80=99s perspective, this is b=
ad: The bank wants all of its top executives to be energetic brilliant peop=
le who=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>run the bank, who would make great CEOs els=
ewhere, but who nonetheless choose to stay at the bank without a shot at th=
e CEO job. There are various ways to create that sort of loyalty:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Money. If being the No. 7 person at y=
our firm pays more than being the CEO elsewhere then hey that=E2=80=99s gre=
at. There are businesses where this works, though it is hard to pull off in=
 investment banking.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Culture. If a=
ll of your top executives have worked all their lives at your firm, if all =
their friends are there, if they look down on every other firm and find the=
 idea of working elsewhere unimaginable, then they will stay.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Partnership. This is related, but slightly diff=
erent. I used to work at Goldman Sachs Group Inc., which more than most of =
the big public investment banks tried to retain <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32361283.264411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMTUvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1jZW8tZGF2aWQt=
c29sb21vbi13YW50cy1oaXMtYmFua2Vycy1iYWNrLWF0LXRoZS1vZmZpY2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDg=
xMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdX=
RtX3Rlcm09MjMwODEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B579461b3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">  some of its old partnership culture</a>, though there =
are a lot of reports that it is fraying under its current CEO, David Solomo=
n.=C2=A0One advantage of that culture is that, in a partnership, everyone g=
ets to feel a bit like a CEO. =E2=80=9CSince the late 1800s, Goldman partne=
rs have weighed in on the firm=E2=80=99s direction,=E2=80=9D the Wall Stree=
t Journal <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32361283=
.264411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDY=
tMTMvbmFrZWQtc2hvcnQtc2VsbGVyLWdldHMtaW4tdHJvdWJsZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwODEwMjNfTU=
9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVyb=
T0yMzA4MTAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdd29a3c=
c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  wrote in June</a>. =E2=80=9CPartners sometimes overruled the=
 CEO or persuaded him to go along with their plans. For a long time, the CE=
O was viewed as one of many, less a benign dictator and more the bank=E2=80=
=99s public face and standard-bearer.=E2=80=9D If you can make =E2=80=9Cpar=
tner=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>feel=C2=A0</em>like the top job, rather than =E2=80=
=9CCEO,=E2=80=9D you can keep a lot of good people around feeling satisfied=
 that they=E2=80=99ve made it to the top.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">Constant coups? If every top executive=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>bec=
ome CEO by bumping off the current CEO, they might stay motivated. This has=
 problems.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I don=E2=80=99t know, y=
ou couldmake all the top people sign 10-year employment contracts 15 minute=
s before you announce the new CEO.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Sridhar Natarajan reports =
on the apparently amicable <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/32361283.264411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbG=
