<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The stereotypical way that a management consul=
ting interview works is that you get asked questions like =E2=80=9Chow much=
 pepperoni=C2=A0 is sold in the US every year,=E2=80=9D and then you reason=
 your way to some estimate of the answer. This stuff is a classic of manage=
ment consulting interviewing not because you are expected to know the answe=
r, or because management consultants spend their days guessing how much pep=
peroni is sold in the US each year, but because the process of answering th=
e question demonstrates your ability to reason through a problem, think on =
the fly=C2=A0and act confident in meetings, and also it=C2=A0gives some sen=
se of your practical understanding of the world. Or something. I don=E2=80=
=99t know. I have not been in a management consulting interview since colle=
ge, and I wasn=E2=80=99t great at them then. That=E2=80=99s not the point. =
The point is that management consultants do not actually spend their days g=
uessing how much pepperoni is sold in the US each year. <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32361283.264411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMDkvc3VtbWVyLWludGVybnNoaXAtcHJv=
Z3JhbXMtb2ZmZXItZ29vZC1iYWQtYW5kLXVnbHktd29yay1leHBlcmllbmNlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQ=
wODEwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlci=
Z1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA4MTAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBd6d278eb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  Or do they</a>?</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A few weeks into his college summer internship=
 at a consulting firm in 2015, a guy (let=E2=80=99s call him Calvin) got hi=
s big chance to make a good impression. He was assigned to help a private e=
quity firm assess an acquisition target=E2=80=94in this case, a company tha=
t manufactured pepperoni. =E2=80=9CI was 21 years old, researching question=
s I don=E2=80=99t know if anyone knows the answer to, like the market size =
for pepperoni in the US,=E2=80=9D says Calvin, who asked that his name not =
be used to preserve his current professional reputation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After two 80-hour weeks of research, Calvin=E2=
=80=99s peers in the sweaty intern bullpen in an office off New York=E2=80=
=99s Times Square were ready to present their findings. But he still lacked=
 the crucial number. =E2=80=9CI was the bottleneck, and I wasn=E2=80=99t do=
ing a great job communicating to my boss,=E2=80=9D he says. His solution? =
=E2=80=9CI found a claim from some executive online that the market size fo=
r pepperoni is enough that you could blanket the entire USA with a thin lay=
er,=E2=80=9D says Calvin. He spent hours putting together and executing a p=
lan. He calculated the area of the entire continental US (3,120,426 square =
miles). Then he came up with the area of a single pepperoni slice: If the d=
iameter of a circular slice of pepperoni is half an inch, each pepperoni is=
 0.196 square inches. The area of the continental US, divided by the area o=
f a single pepperoni slice, equals 15,920,541 slices, which he labeled the =
national pepperoni volume. Finally, he multiplied that volume by price (10=
=C2=A2 per slice, based on his market research) to come up with the country=
=E2=80=99s pepperoni market size at $1,592,054 per year.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When Calvin tracked down his bosses to deliver=
 this key figure, they weren=E2=80=99t interested. They considered his appr=
oach ridiculous.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What? What? They worked at a management consul=
ting firm! They hired people specifically for their propensity, when confro=
nted with a question like =E2=80=9Chow much pepperoni is sold in the US eac=
h year,=E2=80=9D to use inputs like =E2=80=9Cthe area of the continental US=
.=E2=80=9D They should have promoted him. What an amazing story. This is li=
ke if a utility company came to McKinsey &amp; Co. and said =E2=80=9Cwe nee=
d to design some manhole covers, what shape should we make them,=E2=80=9D a=
nd the first-day McKinsey intern was like =E2=80=9Cwait wait <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32361283.264411/aHR0cHM6Ly9sZWdh=
Y3kudmF1bHQuY29tL2Jsb2dzL2ludGVydmlld2luZy9zYW1wbGUtaW50ZXJ2aWV3LXF1ZXN0aW9=
ucy13aHktYXJlLW1hbmhvbGUtY292ZXJzLXJvdW5k/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd026f752=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;"> I will handle this</a>.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess my only quibble is that=C2=A0the math =
in this anecdote is wildly wrong: The calculation divides 3 million square =
<em>miles</em> by 0.196 pepperonis per square <em>inch</em> to get a far-to=
o-low 16 million pepperonis per year, or just $1.6 million at 10 cents per =
pepperoni. If you do the math correctly, then=C2=A03.1 million square miles=
 is=C2=A0roughly <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
2361283.264411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud29sZnJhbWFscGhhLmNvbS9pbnB1dD9pPWFyZWFzK29m=
K3RoZSt1bml0ZWQrc3RhdGVzK2luK3NxdWFyZStpbmNoZXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB23=
82ce93" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> 12.5 quadrillion square inches</a>, or roughly 64 quadrill=
ion pepperonis, or roughly $6.4 quadrillion of pepperoni sales per year at =
10 cents a piece, or roughly 60=C2=A0times the gross domestic product of <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32361283.264411/aHR0=
cHM6Ly9kYXRhLndvcmxkYmFuay5vcmcvaW5kaWNhdG9yL05ZLkdEUC5NS1RQLkNE/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB83fc3d0d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the world</a>. Bullish for this pepperoni=
 acquisition.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(Since I wrote that paragraph, Businessweek co=
rrected the math to get $6.4 quadrillion. Or, =E2=80=9Ccorrected.=E2=80=9D)=
</p>
